Problem 2

  1. Write a custom R function for any one of the following descriptive statistics: median, mode, standard deviation, variance. Demonstrate that it produces the same value as the base R function given some set of numbers.
my_variance <- function(x) {
  sum_x <- sum(x)
  length_x <- length(x)
  sum_deviations_squared <- sum((x-mean(x))^2)
  variance_x <- sum_deviations_squared/length_x
  return(variance_x)
}

my_variance(1:10)
## [1] 8.25
var(1:10)
## [1] 9.166667
my_variance <- function(x) {
  sum_x <- sum(x)
  length_x <- length(x)-1
  sum_deviations_squared <- sum((x-mean(x))^2)
  variance_x <- sum_deviations_squared/length_x
  return(variance_x)
}

my_variance(1:10)
## [1] 9.166667

Confidence level: 85 with Google))

Problem 3

  1. Imagine the same instructor taught a morning, afternoon, and evening section of the same course. And, the average scores for each section on a midterm were 85% for the morning, 90% for the afternoon, and 93% for the evening sections. Create a data.frame representing these means for each section. Then, use ggplot2 to plot the means as bar graph. (hint you will need one vector for the class sections, and one vector for the means. Then you can combine them into a data.frame before plotting them)
  means <- c(85, 90, 93)
  course <- c("morning", "afternoon", "evening")
  my_data <- data.frame(means, course)

library(ggplot2)
  
  ggplot(my_data, aes(course,means))+
  geom_bar(stat = "identity")+
  ylab("Grades")+
  xlab("Section")+
  theme_classic()+
  ggtitle("Average Scores For Each Section On a Midterm")

Then plot data.frame using ggplot2 as a bar graph.
  instructor <- c("one", "one", "one", "two", "two", "two")
  course <- c("morning", "afternoon", "evening","morning", "afternoon", "evening")
  grades <- c(75, 78, 80, 88, 76, 63)
  my_data <- data.frame(instructor, course, grades)
  
  ggplot(my_data, aes(course,grades, group=instructor, fill=instructor))+

Problem 6

6.Repeat the above, except in addition to calculating the mean for each year, also calculate the standard deviation for “healthy life expectancy at birth” for each year. Then, add error bars to your graph using the +1 and -1 standard deviations from the means for each year.

mean_hle <- whr %>%
  filter(year >= 2010,
         year <= 2015) %>%
  group_by(year) %>%
  summarize(mean_healthy = mean(Healthy.life.expectancy.at.birth, na.rm = TRUE),
            sd_healthy = sd(Healthy.life.expectancy.at.birth, na.rm = TRUE))
## `summarise()` ungrouping output (override with `.groups` argument)
ggplot(mean_hle, aes(year,mean_healthy), color=year)+
  geom_bar(stat="identity")+
  geom_errorbar(aes(ymin = mean_healthy-sd_healthy,
                    ymax = mean_healthy + sd_healthy),
                width = .25)+
  ylab("Mean_HLE")+
  xlab("Year")+
  theme_classic()+
  ggtitle("Healthy Life Expectancy At Birth")
